{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493071","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493071"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:55:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:55:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1214"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1214","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1214"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.04,0.51,0.07,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1214"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109672"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1214","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1214"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1214"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92075"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"6400"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13612"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13613"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35494"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35495"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37219"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44338"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109672","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109672"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 28-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a one day history of right-sided testicular pain of gradual onset. This is associated with some burning on micturition. There is no history of trauma, fever, malaise, dysuria, haematuria or urethral discharge. He had sex with a new partner four days ago. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, the left side of the scrotum and contents are normal, the right scrotum is swollen, reddened, and tender on palpation. Elevation of the scrotum provides some pain relief. The cremasteric reflex is present bilaterally. Scrotal ultrasonography shows an enlarged epididymis on the right with increased blood flow. Some empirical treatment is to be started. Urine MSU and NAAT are pending.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following antibiotic regimens would be most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Single dose IM ceftriaxone and single dose IM azithromycin","Single dose IM azithromycin and oral trimethoprim for two weeks","Single dose IM ceftriaxone and oral doxycycline for two weeks","Single dose IM ceftriaxone and oral trimethoprim for two weeks","Single dose IM azithromycin and oral doxycycline for one week"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u2019s presentation is consistent with acute epididymo-orchitis and in a young adult is most likely secondary to a sexually transmitted infection (STI), such as \u003Cem\u003EChlamydia trachomatis,\u003C/em\u003E \u003Cem\u003ENeisseria gonorrhoeae\u003C/em\u003E or \u003Cem\u003EMycoplasma genitalium\u003C/em\u003E. The patient has no other medical history of urinary issues and has had a new sexual partner thus his symptoms are less likely to be caused by a urinary tract infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis diagnosis is consistent with the gradual onset of unilateral testicular pain\u00a0and\u00a0recent sexual activity with a new partner. The pain is also characteristically relieved with elevation of the scrotum. Ultrasonography usually demonstrates increased blood flow. Until recently the most appropriate empirical antibiotic regimen for suspected chlamydia and/or gonorrhoea was a\u00a0once only\u00a0dose of \u003Cstrong\u003Eceftriaxone\u003C/strong\u003E and azithromycin\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe current guidelines recommend that treatment should be targeted at the two most likely causative pathogens, \u003Cem\u003EChlamydia trachomatis \u003C/em\u003Eand \u003Cem\u003ENeisseria gonorrhoeae\u003C/em\u003E. The recommended regimen is a \u003Cstrong\u003Esingle dose IM ceftriaxone and oral doxycycline for two weeks. \u003C/strong\u003EIf the patient is reluctant to take the two week medication then the single dose of ceftriaxone should be accompanied by a single dose of azithromycin, with the latter being repeated in one week.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst a urine sample will be sent off for nucleic acid amplification testing (NAAT), the results will not be obtained for 24 hours and treatment should commenced in the interim.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETrimethoprim, ciprofloxacin or trimethoprim with sulfamethoxazole are the recommended treatment in older men, where the underlying cause is thought to caused by a urinary tract pathogen, such as \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli, \u003C/em\u003Eand should be based on the results of the urine culture.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most cases of acute epididymo-orchitis in young men are due to either Chlamydia trachomatis or Neisseria gonorrhoeae.","Empirical treatment for epididymo-orchitis in sexually active young men should cover both Chlamydia trachomatis and Neisseria gonorrhoeae.","Urine nucleic acid amplification testing should be performed, but treatment should not be delayed while awaiting results."],"references":["Ong JJ, Bourne C, Dean JA et al. Australian sexually transmitted infection (STI) management guidelines for use in primary care 2022 update. Sexual Health. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36356948/","Rupp TJ, Leslie SW. Epididymitis. [Updated 2023 Jul 17]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430814/ Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430814/","Banyra O, Shulyak A. Acute epididymo-orchitis: staging and treatment. Cent European J Urol. 2012;65(3):139-43. doi: 10.5173/ceju.2012.03.art8. Epub 2012 Sep 4. PMID: 24578950; PMCID: PMC3921787. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3921787/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92075"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1214"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92075","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92075"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-24T13:47:55+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-24T13:47:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1214"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109672"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"37","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/37"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf46","name":"Sexual Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group